1. finis aequi iuris, ‘the close of equitable law.' That such is the meaning of Tacitus would appear from the follow- ing sentence, stating that the subsequent course os legislation, except such as was directed to the repression of crime, aimed at personal or party objects‚ rather than the welsare of the whole state. It is easy to point to laws which cannot be justly so described; and Tacitus may have really meant no more than that the enactment of this code' was the last occasion on which all orders had united in a comprehensive attempt at legislation. He appears to know nothing of the dis- tinction implied in the narrative of Livy and asserted by Cicero (de Rep. 2. 37, 63), that the two last Tables were ‘ini- quissimae' The genera-l Roman reve·- rence sor the code is expressed by Cicero, and also by Livy, who calls the first ten Tables ‘fons omnis publici privatique iuris' (3. 34, 7).
